Here’s a clean, dev-friendly setup that shows logs in your terminal and also writes them to files.

Configure the app → log server
- Start the log server
  - Terminal A: npm run log:server
  - Options:
    - LOG_SERVER_PORT=4317 LOG_DIR=logs npm run log:server
- Point the app at it
  - EITHER set an env var (no proxy):
    - Create .env.local with VITE_LOG_SERVER_URL=http://127.0.0.1:4317/log
  - OR proxy through Vite for same-origin:
    - vite.config.ts → add:
      server: { proxy: { '/log': 'http://127.0.0.1:4317' } }
    - And .env.local: VITE_LOG_SERVER_URL=/log

Run dev with log tailing
- Terminal B: npm run dev 2>&1 | tee -a logs/dev-$(date +%Y%m%d).log
- Terminal C (tail logs): tail -f logs/watch-$(date +%Y%m%d).log

Optional: run both together
- Add script:
  - "dev:with-logs": "npm run log:server & npm run dev"
  - Note: On Windows, use start /B or install concurrently if you want nicer control.

Show logs inside Vite (optional plugin)
- vite.config.ts:
  - Add a tiny plugin to log requests and write to a file:
    import fs from 'fs'; import path from 'path';
    const reqLogPath = path.join('logs', `vite-requests-${new Date().toISOString().slice(0,10).replace(/-/g,'')}.log`);
    export default defineConfig({
      plugins: [{
        name: 'request-logger',
        configureServer(server) {
          server.middlewares.use((req, res, next) => {
            const line = JSON.stringify({ ts: new Date().toISOString(), method: req.method, url: req.url });
            try { fs.mkdirSync('logs', { recursive: true }); fs.appendFileSync(reqLogPath, line + '\n'); } catch {}
            console.log('[vite]', req.method, req.url);
            next();
          });
        }
      }],
      server: { proxy: { '/log': 'http://127.0.0.1:4317' } }
    });

What you’ll see
- Browser/client errors: captured by ErrorBoundary + window error hooks and POSTed to the log server; appear in logs/watch-YYYYMMDD.log and your dev console.
- App lifecycle/info: use logInfo('context', 'message') to emit to both console and file.
- Vite request log (optional): each dev request written to logs/vite-requests-YYYYMMDD.log.

Nice-to-haves
- Add a “Tail logs” panel in-app by fetching GET /ping every few seconds and reading the file with a tiny Node endpoint (or just keep using tail -f).
- Persist VITE_LOG_SERVER_URL in settings UI if you switch between local/remote log sinks.

Here’s the latest Vite guidance (as of September 10, 2025) and a concrete setup to capture dev errors to your terminal and an on-disk log.

What’s “latest”
- Plugin API — use configureServer/configurePreviewServer to add dev/preview middlewares and tap the ViteDevServer instance. ([vite.dev](https://vite.dev/guide/api-plugin/?utm_source=openai))
- Env and modes — expose client-side values via import.meta.env and .env files (.env, .env.local, .env.development, etc.). Vars must be prefixed with VITE_. ([vite.dev](https://vite.dev/guide/env-and-mode/?utm_source=openai))

Dev error logging setup
- Env
  - Create .env.local:
    - VITE_LOG_SERVER_URL=/log
- Vite proxy (same-origin POSTs)
  - vite.config.ts:
    - server: { proxy: { '/log': 'http://127.0.0.1:4317' } }
- Vite plugin (request/error taps)
  - Add a tiny plugin to log requests and forward server-side errors:
    import fs from 'fs';
    import path from 'path';
    import type { Plugin } from 'vite';

    function devLogPlugin(): Plugin {
      const logDir = 'logs';
      const dayTag = new Date().toISOString().slice(0,10).replace(/-/g,'');
      const reqLog = path.join(logDir, `vite-requests-${dayTag}.log`);
      const errLog = path.join(logDir, `vite-errors-${dayTag}.log`);
      fs.mkdirSync(logDir, { recursive: true });

      const append = (p: string, line: any) => {
        try { fs.appendFileSync(p, JSON.stringify(line) + '\n'); } catch {}
      };

      return {
        name: 'dev-log',
        configureServer(server) {
          // Request logging
          server.middlewares.use((req, _res, next) => {
            append(reqLog, { ts: new Date().toISOString(), method: req.method, url: req.url });
            next();
          });
          // Server error logging (SSR/render or internal errors)
          server.httpServer?.on('clientError', (err, socket) => {
            append(errLog, { ts: new Date().toISOString(), type: 'clientError', msg: err.message });
            socket.end('HTTP/1.1 400 Bad Request\r\n\r\n');
          });
          server.ws.on('error', (err) => {
            append(errLog, { ts: new Date().toISOString(), type: 'wsError', msg: String(err?.message || err) });
          });
          return () => {
            // Post-middlewares can be added here if needed
          };
        },
      };
    }

    export default defineConfig({
      plugins: [devLogPlugin()],
      server: { proxy: { '/log': 'http://127.0.0.1:4317' } },
    });
  - Why this matches docs: configureServer is the supported hook to add dev middlewares and access the server instance. ([vite.dev](https://vite.dev/guide/api-plugin/?utm_source=openai))

- Client error forwarding (browser → file)
  - You already have:
    - Global listeners in src/main.tsx for window error/unhandledrejection
    - ErrorBoundary → logError(...)
    - src/utils/logger.ts posting to VITE_LOG_SERVER_URL (proxied to http://127.0.0.1:4317/log)
  - This lets browser errors reach the Node watch log (logs/watch-YYYYMMDD.log) while Vite plugin logs requests and server-side errors.

- Run
  - Terminal A: npm run log:server
  - Terminal B: npm run dev
  - Tail logs:
    - tail -f logs/watch-$(date +%Y%m%d).log
    - tail -f logs/vite-requests-$(date +%Y%m%d).log
    - tail -f logs/vite-errors-$(date +%Y%m%d).log

Notes and options
- You can point VITE_LOG_SERVER_URL directly to http://127.0.0.1:4317/log without the proxy; the proxy just avoids CORS in dev.
- For preview builds, mirror the middleware with configurePreviewServer if you want request/error logs during vite preview too. ([vite.dev](https://vite.dev/guide/api-plugin/?utm_source=openai))
- Env pitfalls: remember only VITE_* are exposed to the client; restart Vite after editing .env files. ([vite.dev](https://vite.dev/guide/env-and-mode/?utm_source=openai))

Want me to add the exact vite.config.ts changes to your repo and expose a tiny “Logs” panel in the UI to tail today’s file live?

